column1: #Text=Slow-cooking dinosaur eggs may have contributed to extinction , say scientists

#Text=A joint research team from the University of Calgary , American Museum of Natural History , and Florida State University announced on Monday that the eggs of non- avian dinosaurs such as the duck-billed dinosaur took as long as six months to hatch , far longer than had previously been believed .
#Text=Protoceratops andrewsi display at the American Museum of Natural History .
#Text=We could literally count [ the growth rings ] to see how long each dinosaur had been developing .
#Text=— Gregory Erickson of Florida State University
#Text=Bird eggs incubate for 11 to 85 days , about half the time of most other egg-laying vertebrates .
#Text=Scientists had thought dinosaur eggs were more like those of modern birds than modern reptiles , but this long hatch time is far more reminiscent of monitor lizard than magpie .

#Text=The scientists reached this conclusion by comparing CT scans of the teeth of dinosaur embryos of two different species , the Protoceratops andrewsi , which had eggs weighing under 200 gram s , and Hypacrosaurus stebingeri , a type of duck-billed dinosaur that had eggs twenty times that size .
#Text=They observed the von Ebner lines , patterns that form in vertebrate teeth as they grow , to determine how long the overall developmental process was taking .
#Text=" They 're kind of like tree rings , but they 're put down daily , " said Florida State University co-author Gregory Erickson . "
